## A1 — Recognition Post (Day 1)

**Facebook — Recognition**

You have probably noticed it more than once. The hesitation at a green light. The unexplained scrape on the fender. The moment in the parking lot that made your stomach drop.

And then you told yourself: it was just once. They were tired. It was dark.

This article is about what happens when it is no longer just once.

When should someone with dementia stop driving? How do you have the conversation? What do you do when they refuse? And what are the alternatives in the GTA once the keys come off the hook?

https://www.arcadiahomecare.ca/resources/dementia-memory-care/dementia-when-to-stop-driving/?utm_source=facebook&utm_medium=social&utm_campaign=dementia-when-to-stop-driving

**LinkedIn — Recognition**

One of the most common questions families ask after a dementia diagnosis: when is it no longer safe to drive?

There is no single answer, but there are patterns. Getting lost on familiar routes. Delayed reactions at intersections. New dents with no explanation. Confusion in heavy traffic.

This guide covers the signs, how to have the conversation, what Ontario physicians are required to report, and what transportation alternatives exist in the GTA.

https://www.arcadiahomecare.ca/resources/dementia-memory-care/dementia-when-to-stop-driving/?utm_source=linkedin&utm_medium=social&utm_campaign=dementia-when-to-stop-driving

**Instagram — Recognition**

The hesitation at intersections that used to be automatic.
The scrape on the bumper with no explanation.
The near-miss your parent brushed off.

You noticed. You are not overreacting.

This guide covers when driving is no longer safe, how to have the conversation, and what to do when a parent refuses to stop.

Link in bio.

