## A2 — Reframe Post (Days 3–5)

### Reframe 1: Good days do not erase bad ones

**Facebook — Reframe 1**

"But they drove fine yesterday."

That is what makes this so hard. A person in early-stage dementia may drive well on Monday and dangerously on Wednesday. The inconsistency makes families second-guess what they saw.

But the inconsistency is the warning sign. Safe driving requires reliable judgment, not occasional judgment.

If you are watching a parent's driving and wondering whether what you saw was serious: it probably was.

https://www.arcadiahomecare.ca/resources/dementia-memory-care/dementia-when-to-stop-driving/?utm_source=facebook&utm_medium=social&utm_campaign=dementia-when-to-stop-driving

**LinkedIn — Reframe 1**

In early-stage dementia, driving ability is often inconsistent rather than consistently impaired. Families see good days and question whether the concerning days were anomalies.

They were not. Safe driving requires reliable executive function, not intermittent executive function.

For families and professionals navigating this question, here is a practical guide covering the signs, the Ontario physician reporting path, and alternatives.

https://www.arcadiahomecare.ca/resources/dementia-memory-care/dementia-when-to-stop-driving/?utm_source=linkedin&utm_medium=social&utm_campaign=dementia-when-to-stop-driving

**Instagram — Reframe 1**

"But they drove fine yesterday."

That is what makes this hard. Good days do not cancel out dangerous ones. The inconsistency is the warning sign.

Safe driving requires reliable judgment. Not occasional judgment.

Link in bio for the full guide.

### Reframe 2: This is not about taking something away

**Facebook — Reframe 2**

Driving is independence. It is adulthood. It is control. Asking a parent to stop feels like taking all three away at once.

But here is what families tell us: when they planned the replacement before the removal, the conversation went differently. When their parent knew how they would still get to the pharmacy, the doctor, their friend's house, the loss felt less total.

Remove the driving. Replace the independence.

https://www.arcadiahomecare.ca/resources/dementia-memory-care/dementia-when-to-stop-driving/?utm_source=facebook&utm_medium=social&utm_campaign=dementia-when-to-stop-driving

**LinkedIn — Reframe 2**

The most effective approach to the "stop driving" conversation is not about the driving. It is about what replaces it.

Families who plan transportation alternatives before removing the keys report less resistance, less resentment, and a smoother transition.

Wheel-Trans, companion driving, volunteer programs, and home care with built-in errand support are all options in the GTA. The article covers each one.

https://www.arcadiahomecare.ca/resources/dementia-memory-care/dementia-when-to-stop-driving/?utm_source=linkedin&utm_medium=social&utm_campaign=dementia-when-to-stop-driving

**Instagram — Reframe 2**

Driving represents independence.
Removing it without replacing it feels like a punishment.

Replace it first.

Plan the alternative before you take the keys. The conversation goes differently when your parent knows how they will still get where they need to go.

Link in bio.

### Reframe 3: You have options when they refuse

**Facebook — Reframe 3**

What do you do when your parent refuses to stop driving and you believe they are a danger?

In Ontario, you have options. Their family physician is legally required to report conditions that affect driving fitness. You can ask the doctor to start that process. The ministry can suspend the licence or require a formal driving assessment.

You do not have to convince your parent alone.

https://www.arcadiahomecare.ca/resources/dementia-memory-care/dementia-when-to-stop-driving/?utm_source=facebook&utm_medium=social&utm_campaign=dementia-when-to-stop-driving

**LinkedIn — Reframe 3**

Ontario physicians are legally mandated to report medical conditions that may make a patient unfit to drive. This includes dementia.

For families unable to convince a parent to stop driving voluntarily, the physician reporting path provides an objective, third-party intervention. The Ministry of Transportation can suspend the licence or require a DriveABLE assessment.

This guide outlines the full process, including practical interim measures when the situation is urgent.

https://www.arcadiahomecare.ca/resources/dementia-memory-care/dementia-when-to-stop-driving/?utm_source=linkedin&utm_medium=social&utm_campaign=dementia-when-to-stop-driving

**Instagram — Reframe 3**

What do you do when they refuse to stop?

You have options. In Ontario, their doctor is legally required to report conditions that affect driving fitness. You can ask them to start the process.

You do not have to convince your parent alone.

Link in bio for the full guide.

