## A4 — Quiet Authority Post (Day 11–12)

**LinkedIn — Primary**

The driving conversation is one of the most common inflection points we see in families navigating early-to-mid-stage dementia.

It is rarely about the car. It is about what the car represents: independence, competence, normalcy. And it is the moment many families first realize they need a broader support plan, not just for driving, but for the trajectory the driving concern reveals.

For healthcare professionals who encounter this question in practice, here is a guide we share with families. It covers the Ontario physician reporting process, DriveABLE assessments, practical interim measures, and GTA transportation alternatives.

https://www.arcadiahomecare.ca/resources/dementia-memory-care/dementia-when-to-stop-driving/?utm_source=linkedin&utm_medium=social&utm_campaign=dementia-when-to-stop-driving

**LinkedIn — Link-optional alternative**

When a family calls us about driving safety, it is rarely the first concern. It is the one that finally makes the others undeniable.

The stove. The wandering. The medication. The driving.

Each one is manageable on its own. Together, they tell a story about a level of risk that has exceeded what one person can monitor alone.

If you work with families navigating this trajectory, the article below covers the driving question specifically, including Ontario-specific reporting paths and practical alternatives.

